Modified internal and external geometry also permits operation with a wide range of non Colt-spec platforms such as the HK® 416 and MR556A1, M27 IAR, British SA-80, FN® SCAR™ MK 16/16S, and others. A redesigned bolt catch notch in the rear of the magazine provides increased bolt catch clearance, while an over-travel stop on the spine helps ensure the magazine will not over-insert on compatible weapons.

Similar to the MOE PMAG, the GEN M3 features a long-life stainless steel spring, four-way anti-tilt follower and constant-curve internal geometry for reliable feeding, and simple tool-less disassembly to ease cleaning. In addition, an included pop-off Impact/Dust Cover can optionally be used to minimize debris intrusion and protect against potential damage during storage and transit. Low profile ribs and new aggressive front and rear texture gives positive control of the GEN M3 in all environments, and a paint pen dot matrix has been added to the bottom panel of the body to allow easy marking by the end user for identification. The new, easy to disassemble flared floorplate aids extraction and handling of the magazine while providing improved drop protection, but is slightly slimmer than before for better compatibility with tight double and triple magazine pouches.

The next-generation PMAG 30 Window GEN M3 is a 30-round 5.56x45 NATO (.223 Remington) polymer magazine for AR15/M4 compatible weapons that features transparent windows to allow rapid visual identification of approximate number of rounds remaining.

title: For Sale:  Remington Model 11 - 12GA
postcontent:
Mfg in 1927, this gun has a smooth barrel with the Browning patents stamped on top of it and a cylinder fixed choke (CYL stamped).  Choke is ideal for Home Defense … spreads out that pattern!

Modeled after the Browning A-5 design it has been one of my favorites over the years.  This is not a museum piece, so if you are looking for a 100% gun that was purchased new, locked away somewhere and ignored this is not the gun for you.  If, however, you are looking for a gun that has been appreciated and enjoyed for its intended purpose (Shooting) then you might want to consider this one.  I bought this gun in 1988 or 1989 from a friend who had used it his whole life (it had been his father’s gun).  I did a little shooting with it early on and it always worked flawlessly for me but I have not used it much of late.  This is a shotgun that shows both its use and appreciation.  It has been well maintained but it does show wear, especially on the forearm which also has a hairline crack on each side.  The buttstock has a few scratches but is in remarkable condition.  The bluing looks nice but under bright light you can see specks missing at the rear of the barrel and some wear at other spots on the receiver and rest of the barrel.

Overall it is a very nice looking gun that has aged wonderfully and is a joy to shoot. 

I’m looking for $475 or the best offer.  If no one likes it enough, that’s ok … I’m willing to keep it.

I’m looking for a local cash sale … No trades.  
I will transfer face-to-face in IN w/ Bill of sale and your DL.
I will reply only to individuals who provide their valid phone number.
I will remove ad when/if weapon is no longer available.

title: For Sale:  Collector grade US Springfield M-1 Garand, NFR
postcontent: Collector grade US Springfield M-1 Garand, NFR. A beautiful M-1 serial # 3,865,901. No import marks. I have not restored it. Barrel is 6-45 with a TE of 2.75 and a Muzzle of just under 1. Bright, shiny bore. All parts are correct for serial number and date. Metal is excellent with little wear. Stock has some dings which are light except for one deep one (rack mark?) just behind the front sling swivel. Stock has a light hit SA/NFR but it has not been sanded and is very readable. The ordnance wheel is an uneven hit but deep on one side. There is a circled P firing proof on the front of the grip as well as J 43 which I’m sure is a rack number. Bottom of grip has a small ordnance symbol. Walnut stock has tiger stripe graining all the way on the left and about halfway on the right. Hand guards are nice walnut as well. No cracks, repairs, or chips in wood anywhere. Wide gas chamber with cross slot plug marked P. Gas cylinder is Springfield with the letter K on the top flat and a single punch mark on the bayonet lug. Chamber is bright indicating it has not been re-parked. Type 3 lock bar, squared end, rear sights. SA 14 trigger housing with 7 SA hammer, SA-11 safety and stamped trigger guard. Op rod is 9 SA unmodified. #12 follower. #19 SA bolt with heat lot A-8. Lock up is nice and tight. I have no documentation to prove originality but I've collected a long time and it looks that way to me.
